// TEST: exec_ts_generic_enum_codegen
// EXPECT: output "full=7;empty=0"
// EXPECT: targets js, ts, python, rust, go
//
// A GENERIC user-defined enum (`enum Box[T] { Full(T), Empty }`), constructed at
// a CONCRETE instantiation (`Box[Int]`) and matched. Regression fixture for
// Q-ts-generic-enum-codegen.
//
// Runs on ALL FIVE targets. This is the first generic *user enum* exec fixture
// in the suite. It originally surfaced two independent codegen bugs, both now
// fixed: the TS arity bug fixed here (Q-ts-generic-enum-codegen) and a Go
// enum-receiver/instantiation defect (Q-go-generic-enum-codegen) — the Go
// backend emitted an invalid generic enum-marker receiver `func (BoxFull[T any])`
// and bare generic struct literals/type-switch cases; fixed in `go.rs` so `go`
// was added to the target set above. All five build, execute, and print
// `full=7;empty=0`.
//
// TS defect (TS2314 "Generic type requires N type argument(s)"): the enum union
// type ALIAS was emitted with concretized/mismatched generic arity relative to
// the per-variant interfaces — e.g. the alias rendered like `Box<number>` while
// the variant interfaces were `Box_Full<T>` / `Box_Empty<T>`, so the alias body
// referenced variant interfaces with the wrong number of type arguments and
// `tsc --noEmit` rejected the file before any narrowing concern. The fix makes
// the union alias and the variant interfaces carry CONSISTENT generic-parameter
// arity (`type Box<T> = Box_Full<T> | Box_Empty<T>`, each variant interface
// carrying the same `<T>`), and emits uses with the right type args.
//
// `Full` carries the type param `T` (a positional/tuple payload); `Empty` is a
// unit variant in the same enum so the union mixes a payload-bearing generic
// variant with a payload-free one — the arity-consistency point of the fixture.
//
// The reducer pulls the payload out via a `match` whose `Full(x)` arm binds and
// uses the payload (so Go's unused-local check is satisfied) and whose `Empty`
// arm returns a default.
//
// `main` is intentionally NOT `public` (see hello_world.bock for the Go
// entry-point rationale).
module main

enum Box[T] {
  Full(T)
  Empty
}

fn unwrap_or_zero(b: Box[Int]) -> Int {
  match b {
    Full(x) => return x
    Empty => return 0
  }
}

fn main() -> Void {
  let f: Box[Int] = Full(7)
  let e: Box[Int] = Empty
  println("full=${unwrap_or_zero(f)};empty=${unwrap_or_zero(e)}")
}
